===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[set free]], [[release]] or [[discharge]] (from [[obligation]]s, [[debt]]s, [[responsibility]] etc.). {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=9}}</ref>
#: {{ux|en|You will '''absolve''' a subject from his allegiance.}}
#* {{RQ:Macaulay History of England|III|XIV|410|The Committee divided, and Halifax was '''absolved''' by a majority of fourteen.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To [[resolve]]; to [[explain]]; to [[solve]]. {{defdate|Attested from the late 15<sup>th</sup> century until the mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* '''1595''', {{w|George Peele}}, ''[[w:The Old Wives' Tale (play)|The Old Wives’ Tale]]'', The Malone Society Reprints, 1908, lines 331-332,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/oldwivestale00peeluoft]</sup>
#*: {{...}} he that can monsters tame, laboures atchive, riddles '''absolve''' {{...}}
#* {{RQ:Browne Pseudodoxia Epidemica|Of the blackneſſe of Negroes|page=276|passage=we ſhall not '''abſolve''' the doubt.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[pronounce]] [[free]] from or give [[absolution]] for a [[penalty]], [[blame]], or [[guilt]]. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{lb|en|transitive|legal}} To pronounce not guilty; to grant a [[pardon]] for. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{RQ:Pope Odyssey|XI|121|line=702|'''Abſolves''' the juſt, and dooms the guilty ſouls.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|theology}} To grant a remission of sin; to give [[absolution]] to. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1597|author=[[w:William Shakespeare]]|title=Romeo and Juliet|section=Act 3, Scene 5|passage=To make confession and to be '''absolved'''.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|theology}} To remit a sin; to give absolution for a sin. {{defdate|First attested in the late 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{RQ:Gibbon Roman Empire|VI|LXVII|447|In his name I '''abſolve''' your perjury and ſanctify your arms: follow my footſteps in the paths of glory and ſalvation; and if ſtill ye have ſcruples, devolve on my head the puniſhment and the ſin.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To [[finish]]; to [[accomplish]]. {{defdate|Attested from the late 16<sup>th</sup> century until the early 19<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|book=VII|lines=93–94|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F08CAAAAQAAJ&pg=PP214|passage=and the work begun, how ſoon / '''Abſolv'd''',}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To pass a course or test; to gain credit for a class; to qualify academically.

